ly solution is to let <code>plus5</code> <em>carry</em> its scope (or rather, its parent''s scope) around. This way, <code>x</code> is well-defined and it is bound to the value 5.\r\n<pre class="default prettyprint prettyprinted"></pre>', 'How JavaScript closures do work?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '265-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-08 09:32:46', '2016-09-08 09:32:46', '', 265, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/265-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(267, 1, '2016-09-08 09:42:27', '2016-09-08 09:42:27', 'jQuery is not necessary, and <strong><code>window.location.replace(...)</code></strong> will best simulate an HTTP redirect.\r\n\r\nIt is better than using <code>window.location.href =</code>, because <code>replace()</code> does not keep the originating page in the session history, meaning the user won''t get stuck in a never-ending back-button fiasco. If you want to simulate someone clicking on a link, use <code>location.href</code>. If you want to simulate an HTTP redirect, use <code>location.replace</code>.\r\n\r\n<strong>For example:</strong>\r\n<pre class="default prettyprint prettyprinted"><code><span class="com">// similar behavior as an HTTP redirect</span><span class="pln">\r\nwindow</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">location</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">replace</span><span class="pun">(</span><span class="str">"http://bd-techzone.com"</span><span class="pun">);</span>\r\n\r\n<span class="com">// similar behavior as clicking on a link</span><span class="pln">\r\nwindow</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">location</span><span class="pun">.</span><span class="pln">href </span><span class="pun">=</span> <span class="str">"http:/.com"</span><span class="pun">;</span></code></pre>', 'How to redirect to another page using jQuery?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'redirect-another-page-using-jquery', '', '', '2016-09-08 09:51:36', '2016-09-08 09:51:36', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/?p=267', 0, 'post', '', 0),
