n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1>********************************************</h1>\r\n<h1>Useful Links</h1>\r\n<h2>Some Programming Useful Links</h2>\r\ni. <a href="http://www.shafaetsplanet.com/planetcoding">Programming in Bangla</a>\r\n\r\nii. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/0131997467/httpwwwtuto0a-20">Reference Books 1</a>\r\n\r\niii. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/1438253273/httpwwwtuto0a-20">Reference Books 2</a>\r\n\r\niv. <a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/0130369977/httpwwwtuto0a-20">Reference Books 3</a>\r\n\r\nv. <a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/0929306406/httpwwwtuto0a-20">Reference Books 4</a>\r\n\r\nvi. <a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/1466322543/httpwwwtuto0a-20">Reference Books 5</a>\r\n<h2>Algorithm analysis Links</h2>\r\ni. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amortized_analysis">Amortized analysis</a>\r\n\r\nii. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_heap">Amortized performance comparison of Fibonacci and binomial heap</a>\r\n<h2>Array Useful Links</h2>\r\ni. <a href="http://www.cplusplus.com/doc/tutorial/dynamic/">Allocation of dynamic array</a>\r\n\r\nii.<a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/79923/what-and-where-are-the-stack-and-heap">Stack and heap in computer memory</a>\r\n<h2>Linked List Useful Links</h2>\r\ni. <a href="http://www.sqa.org.uk/e-learning/LinkedDS02CD/page_45.htm">ADT for linked list</a>\r\n\r\nii.<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-organizing_list">Self organizing list</a>\r\n<h2>Stack Useful Links</h2>\r\ni. <a href="http://interactivepython.org/runestone/static/pythonds/BasicDS/WhatisaStack.html">Solve problem using stack</a>\r\n\r\nii. <a href="http://faculty.cs.niu.edu/~hutchins/csci241/eval.htm">Arithmetic expression evaluation</a>\r\n<h2>Queue Useful Links</h2>\r\ni.<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/crowd-control-management-solving-queue-problems-suha-abu-ghosh">Solve problem using queue</a>\r\n\r\nii.<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queue_(abstract_data_type)">Queue ADT</a>\r\n<h2>Tree Useful Links</h2>\r\ni.<a href="http://algs4.cs.princeton.edu/32bst/">Binary search tree, Addition and deletion (Hibbard) of node in a BST-01</a>\r\n\r\nii.<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_search_tree">Binary search tree, Addition and deletion (Hibbard) of node in a BST-02</a>\r\n\r\niii.<a href="http://www.geeksforgeeks.org/avl-tree-set-1-insertion/">AVL tree (step by step construction)-01</a>\r\n\r\niv.<a href="http://cs-study.blogspot.com/2012/11/avl-tree.html">AVL tree (step by step construction)-02</a>\r\n<h1>*********************************************</h1>', 'Teeth pain solution 2016 working solution', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'teeth-pain-solution', '', '', '2016-09-30 16:57:40', '2016-09-30 16:57:40', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/?p=373', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(361, 4, '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '<h2>htmlspecialchars vs. htmlentities</h2>\r\nYou should use <code>htmlspecialchars($strText, ENT_QUOTES)</code> when you just want your string to be XML and HTML safe:\r\n\r\nFor example, encode\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>&amp; to &amp;amp;</li>\r\n 	<li>" to &amp;quot;</li>\r\n 	<li>&lt; to &amp;lt;</li>\r\n 	<li>&gt; to &amp;gt;</li>\r\n 	<li>'' to &amp;#039;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHowever, if you also have additional characters that are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicode">Unicode</a> or uncommon symbols in your text then you should use htmlentities() to ensure they show up properly in your HTML page.\r\n\r\nNotes:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>'' will only be encoded by htmlspecialchars() to &amp;#039; if the ENT_QUOTES option is passed in. &amp;#039; is safer to use then &amp;apos; since older versions of InternetExplorer do not support the &amp;apos; entity.</li>\r\n 	<li>Technically, &gt; does not need to be encoded as per the XML specification, but it is usually encoded too for consistency with the requirement of &lt; being encoded.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'htmlspecialchars vs. htmlentities', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'htmlspecialchars-vs-htmlentities', '', '', '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/?p=361', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(362, 4, '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '<h2>htmlspecialchars vs. htmlentities</h2>\r\nYou should use <code>htmlspecialchars($strText, ENT_QUOTES)</code> when you just want your string to be XML and HTML safe:\r\n\r\nFor example, encode\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>&amp; to &amp;amp;</li>\r\n 	<li>" to &amp;quot;</li>\r\n 	<li>&lt; to &amp;lt;</li>\r\n 	<li>&gt; to &amp;gt;</li>\r\n 	<li>'' to &amp;#039;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHowever, if you also have additional characters that are <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unicode">Unicode</a> or uncommon symbols in your text then you should use htmlentities() to ensure they show up properly in your HTML page.\r\n\r\nNotes:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>'' will only be encoded by htmlspecialchars() to &amp;#039; if the ENT_QUOTES option is passed in. &amp;#039; is safer to use then &amp;apos; since older versions of InternetExplorer do not support the &amp;apos; entity.</li>\r\n 	<li>Technically, &gt; does not need to be encoded as per the XML specification, but it is usually encoded too for consistency with the requirement of &lt; being encoded.</li>\r\n</ul>', 'htmlspecialchars vs. htmlentities', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '361-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '2016-09-10 15:26:01', '', 361, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/361-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
