(421, 4, '2016-10-05 17:55:27', '2016-10-05 17:55:27', 'Mathematics needed for game theory : If you are asking specifically about Mathematics, here are a couple of links: <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://www.cc.gatech.edu/~turk/math_gr.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-qt-tooltip="gatech.edu" data-tooltip="attached">Mathematics for Computer Graphics</a></span> and the books <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://books.google.co.in/books/about/Mathematics_for_Computer_Graphics.html?id=hm_RjwEACAAJ&amp;redir_esc=y" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="google.co.in">Mathematics for Computer Graphics</a></span> and<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://shop.oreilly.com/product/9780596000066.do" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="oreilly.com" data-tooltip="attached">Physics for Game Developers</a></span> (game physics is where most of the math lies, outside of graphics).\r\n\r\nI suggest you also do this series to really get entrenched into the game engine domain (maybe you have done some, maybe not, but this is a useful checklist):\r\n\r\n1. Start using Unity, extensively - do their tutorials, build games, etc. (If you find this overwhelming, start with 2d mobile game engines like Corona SDK or cocos2d-x.\r\n2. Learn open GL and openGL ES, the graphics library interface that most platforms use. If possible, contrast it with DirectX (the similar library for Microsoft platforms). Try to write native 3d apps for various platforms (I suggest at least one mobile, one desktop and one gaming console platform - there should be free or discounted student offerings for access)\r\n3. Once you feel you understand the core principles, also get familiar with 3d graphics tool (I would recommend Blender, which is free, open source and pretty comparable to very expensive commercial alternatives ). Also learn a basic 2d graphic tool like GIMP.\r\n4. At this point, you can start looking at code. There are a few things you can do:\r\n\r\na) read the source of a fully open source graphic engine like godot (see <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="https://github.com/showcases/game-engines" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-qt-tooltip="github.com" data-tooltip="attached">Github list of Game Engines</a></span> and <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_game_engines" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="wikipedia.org">Wikipedia list of game engines</a></span> to find a good one. Try to find a reasonably mature engine, but start with simple ones that you can wrap your head around easily.\r\nb) read the sources of the open source tools in the game development ecosystem (Blender, cocos2d-x and family, Gimp) - one way to do this, once you have a good grasp of the landscape, is, every week, set aside a day to dissect one experience - across 2d graphics, 3d graphics, gaming, IDE and openGL layer. For example, you could do lighting for a few weeks, then do textures for a few weeks, etc. Look at the sources of different tools and see how they implement each of these features.\r\nc) read the sources of the open source components of Unity (see <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://blogs.unity3d.com/2014/08/20/more-open-source-initiatives-from-unity/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="unity3d.com" data-tooltip="attached">More Open-Source Initiatives from Unity  Unity Blog</a></span>, for example ) - try to understand what each part does and how it works.\r\n\r\n5. Once you understand a reasonable portion of the domain''s core code, try to build a game related library, that overcomes some key limitation of current state of the art. Start piece by piece, build upon popular standards at that time (and they can and will change by the time your four years are up), and build an engine that solves a real industry problem.\r\n\r\n6. Continue building components, or build a small but fully functional game engine. Figure out how to get that engine out to people (if it really solves a common problem, people will know about it without much effort).\r\n\r\nIf you have made it this far, you will be well on your way to getting a great job in the game engine field.', 'Mathematics needed for game theory', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mathematics-needed-game-theory', '', '', '2016-10-05 17:55:27', '2016-10-05 17:55:27', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/?p=421', 0, 'post', '', 0),
