(444, 4, '2016-10-08 07:54:14', '2016-10-08 07:54:14', 'how to start web development\r\n\r\n<h2 class="rendered_qtext">Awesome, congrats on taking the first step to learning how to code.\r\n\r\nIf you haven''t already, check out my talk on How to Teach Yourself to Code at Internet Week NY (\r\n</h2>\r\n<div class="qtext_embed thumbnail" style="display: block; position: relative; height: 0px; background: url(''https://img.youtube.com/vi/T0qAjgQFR4c/0.jpg'') center center no-repeat; cursor: pointer; margin-bottom: 1em; width: 602px; padding-top: 338.625px;" data-video-provider="youtube" data-embed="&lt;iframe width=&quot;100%&quot; height=&quot;100%&quot; src=&quot;//www.youtube.com/embed/T0qAjgQFR4c?wmode=opaque&amp;amp;autoplay=1&amp;amp;autohide=1&amp;amp;iv_load_policy=3&amp;amp;enablejsapi=1&quot; frameborder=&quot;0&quot; allowfullscreen&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;" data-yt-id="T0qAjgQFR4c"></div>\r\n<span class="rendered_qtext">). In it, I go through my story of learning how to code on my own using mostly online resources.\r\n\r\nI know there are a lot of questions you want answers to before you get started  and I''ll try to cover as many of them as possible  but honestly the most important thing to know is that you just have to get started somewhere. It''s far more likely that you''ll hurt yourself more by waiting and trying to figure out the perfect place to start than by starting in the wrong place. Once you''ve gotten started coding, it gets easier to answer questions like "Should I learn Ruby or Javascript?"\r\n\r\nThat being said, I do have a little bit of advice that you can use to get started:\r\n\r\nI highly recommend learning Ruby on Rails using some video-based online tutorial as your STARTING POINT. I''ve heard about a lot of people starting with HTML/CSS or even Javascript  and I think that''s a bad idea. You won''t be able to build an interactive website with any of those languages and they''re also pretty complicated to learn on their own. Basically they''re pieces of a much bigger picture.\r\n\r\nThe other downside to starting with HTML/CSS, Javascript, or even Ruby itself is that there''s a lot you can learn that you probably won''t ever need to use. So you''re likely to get bored and give up before you get anywhere interesting enough to keep you motivated. Plus, you''re not going to end up with a gap in your knowledge if you decide to start with Ruby on Rails. Any good beginner Rails tutorial will teach you HTML, CSS, Ruby, and a bit of Javascript along the way. So don''t worry.\r\n\r\nBefore I recommend resources, I''ll make a disclaimer that I created what I think is the perfect introductory class for beginners who want to learn how to code. It''s called One Month Rails and the idea is that I can walk you through the process of building your own simple photo-sharing app (like Pinterest) from scratch over the course of one month. It''s not perfect, and you probably won''t come out of it with the ability to build anything you want to, but you will get one of the nicest and quickest overviews of an extremely powerful web development framework, you''ll have your very own first web application live, and most importantly you''ll feel excited about your progress and want to learn more. Check it out at<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://onemonthrails.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="onemonthrails.com"><u>Learn Ruby On Rails through this Rails tutorial.</u></a></span>  the price is $99.\r\n\r\nAnother good resource is the Ruby on Rails 4 Essential Training tutorial on <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://lynda.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-qt-tooltip="lynda.com"><u>Online video tutorials &amp; training</u></a></span> (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://www.lynda.com/Ruby-Rails-tutorials/Ruby-Rails-4-Essential-Training/139989-2.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener" data-qt-tooltip="lynda.com" data-tooltip="attached"><u>lynda.com Training | Ruby on Rails 4 Essential Training</u></a></span>). This is basically the first class that I started with and it also walks you through all the basics of creating your very first application that is basically a simple blogging platform. You can probably finish it in about a week (there is 12 hours of video), and you''ll feel a little overwhelmed. That''s fine. Keep going and it will make more sense.\r\n\r\nOnce you''ve finished the Lynda tutorial, I''d highly recommend the Ruby on Rails Tutorial by Michael Hartl  which is available as a 15-hour set of videos for $159 here (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://ruby.railstutorial.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="railstutorial.org"><u>Ruby on Rails Tutorial</u></a></span>) or as a free ebook here (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://ruby.railstutorial.org/ruby-on-rails-tutorial-book" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="railstutorial.org"><u>Ruby on Rails Tutorial</u></a></span>). The book is kind of dense, so I wouldn''t recommend starting with it, but if you''ve finished the Lynda tutorial then it''s a perfect next step. And a lot of the concepts should come back to you and be easier to remember the second time around.\r\n\r\nBy the time you''ve finished the Hartl tutorial, you''ll basically have built Twitter from scratch, which is pretty cool.\r\n\r\nFrom that point on, you''ve got a solid foundation of Ruby on Rails itself. I''d recommend checking out some Railscasts (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://railscasts.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="railscasts.com"><u>Ruby on Rails Screencasts</u></a></span>) for tips on building out additional functionality in Rails.\r\n\r\nTwo other options for learning Ruby on Rails are CodeSchool (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="https://www.codeschool.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="codeschool.com"><u>Learn by Doing - Code School</u></a></span>) and Treehouse (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://teamtreehouse.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="teamtreehouse.com"><u>Learn Web Design, Web Development, and More</u></a></span>). I like Code School but I''ve never used Treehouse.\r\n\r\nThen you probably should learn some more basic Ruby and maybe some front-end skills. As far as basic Ruby goes, I''d recommend the following:\r\n\r\nCodecademy has a great Ruby track (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/ruby" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="codecademy.com"><u>Ruby</u></a></span>).\r\n\r\nRubyMonk also has a set of fun, interactive Ruby tutorials (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="https://rubymonk.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="rubymonk.com"><u>RubyMonk - Interactive ruby tutorials to learn Ruby</u></a></span>).\r\n\r\nFor learning HTML and CSS, I''d recommend General Assembly''s Dash (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://dash.generalassemb.ly/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="generalassemb.ly"><u>Dash</u></a></span>), which is probably my favorite front-end tutorial. Code School and Treehouse also have front-end tutorials but I''ve never tried them.\r\n\r\nAt that point you should have a really solid foundation of development. Check out those resources and let me know if you have any questions!</span>\r\n<div id="wUBJLj">\r\n<div id="__w2_kMzfuyg_content_footer" class="ContentFooter AnswerFooter"><span id="yfMrIB"><span class="meta_num"></span></span></div>\r\n</div>', 'How to start web development', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'start-web-development', '', '', '2016-10-08 07:54:14', '2016-10-08 07:54:14', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/?p=444', 0, 'post', '', 0),
