ef="https://www.codeschool.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="codeschool.com"><u>Learn by Doing - Code School</u></a></span>) and Treehouse (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://teamtreehouse.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="teamtreehouse.com"><u>Learn Web Design, Web Development, and More</u></a></span>). I like Code School but I''ve never used Treehouse.\r\n\r\nThen you probably should learn some more basic Ruby and maybe some front-end skills. As far as basic Ruby goes, I''d recommend the following:\r\n\r\nCodecademy has a great Ruby track (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/ruby" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="codecademy.com"><u>Ruby</u></a></span>).\r\n\r\nRubyMonk also has a set of fun, interactive Ruby tutorials (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="https://rubymonk.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="rubymonk.com"><u>RubyMonk - Interactive ruby tutorials to learn Ruby</u></a></span>).\r\n\r\nFor learning HTML and CSS, I''d recommend General Assembly''s Dash (<span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://dash.generalassemb.ly/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="generalassemb.ly"><u>Dash</u></a></span>), which is probably my favorite front-end tutorial. Code School and Treehouse also have front-end tutorials but I''ve never tried them.\r\n\r\nAt that point you should have a really solid foundation of development. Check out those resources and let me know if you have any questions!</span>\r\n<div id="wUBJLj">\r\n<div id="__w2_kMzfuyg_content_footer" class="ContentFooter AnswerFooter"><span id="yfMrIB"><span class="meta_num"></span></span></div>\r\n</div>', 'How to start web development', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '444-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-10-08 07:54:14', '2016-10-08 07:54:14', '', 444, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/444-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(446, 4, '2016-10-08 07:56:05', '2016-10-08 07:56:05', '<h2>php vs asp.net:</h2>\r\nphp vs asp.net:\r\nI take it you mean <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://asp.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="asp.net">ASP.NET</a></span>, for comparison, rather than Classic ASP (starting any new project in Classic ASP would be like choosing Delphi, with an Access database and ODBC connection objects: not actually impossible, but a somewhat pointless investment in a technology the makers acknowledge as legacy).\r\n\r\nIt is generally easier to write bad code in PHP, because it is loosely typed, has variables and globals with arbitrary and sometimes downright misleading names, follows no set pattern to what order arguments should be passed, and is debugged far too often using print_r and die(mysql_error((), and so on, whereas <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://asp.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="asp.net">ASP.NET</a></span> defaults to that hideous red-on-yellow ''Unhandled Exception'' message, accompanied by something cryptic that has been echoed by some tortured module, deep within the depth of the Common Runtime, the moment anyone forgets to make sure the server''s clock isn''t running to international atomic time, or something.\r\n\r\nHaving said that, this does not mean that <b>you</b> personally must contribute to the world''s supply of bad PHP, or that it is impossible to write bad <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link" href="http://asp.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="asp.net">ASP.NET</a></span> (believe me, I have recently finished work on a .NET project where the previous developer would test for true of false, by casting the result of the call ToString and seeing if the first letter was a ''T'' or an ''F'', and would stop something generating an error message by wrapping it in a Try with an empty Catch - I kid you not).\r\n\r\nI''d choose PHP simply because fluidity, if controlled, can be no bad thing, while rigidity appears to induce madness in some people''s minds.\r\n\r\nIt is always going to come down to personal taste, though, and that actually matters more than it probably should. <span class="qlink_container"><a class="external_link tooltip_parent" href="http://asp.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" data-qt-tooltip="asp.net" data-tooltip="attached">ASP.NET</a></span> has a somewhat <i>corporate, beige-trousers</i>, sort of image, while PHP has a sort of <i>"last decade''s bad boy" </i>thing, going on. It barely matters if either of these things is true or not, because if its developers, you need, then choose the technology with the least image problems, because you actually need to be able to find people, to hire.\r\n\r\nFrankly, this is the reason why neither of your options is viable, and you should choose either Ruby or Python.\r\n\r\nActually, ignore me, I suspect I''m just teasing!', 'php vs asp.net', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'php-vs-asp-net', '', '', '2016-10-08 07:56:05', '2016-10-08 07:56:05', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/?p=446', 0, 'post', '', 0);
