(304, 4, '2016-09-08 14:01:11', '2016-09-08 14:01:11', '<h2>Best php framework</h2>\r\n\r\nMy experience says - choice of framework shouldn''t be made with respect to top or best.It should be done based on things like:\r\n\r\nProject Requirements\r\n\r\nSize of Projects\r\n\r\nArchitecture\r\n\r\nDeployment plan\r\n\r\nTeam/Personal Learning curve vs Deadline\r\n\r\nCommunity/official support for the framework\r\n\r\nAnswering these question can direct you to chose certain frameworks - most of the time - given that you have a laundry list of frameworks-feature-list which many of the people shared in their answers.\r\n\r\nI can share my experience regarding this.\r\n\r\nFor projects that is supposed to expand (logically infinitely) and that is supposed to have modules/sections/divisions, etc. I would go for Symfony2.\r\n\r\nFor projects should be fast and with ease with very flexibility - I would go for Laravel.\r\n\r\nI haven''t tried Phalcon yet - but I would use that for projects where performance, memory management, etc are priority [for example - developing a message queuing system].\r\n\r\nUsually for shared hosting small projects - I would go with CodeIgniter. But of course with some tedious steps - Symfony2 and Laravel both can be used in shared hosting.\r\n\r\nAnd so on.\r\n\r\nSee all of these are very popular and time-to-time they are considered as top -- but it solely depends on the situation the developer is in.', 'Best php framework 2016', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '302-revision-v1', '', '', '2016-09-08 14:01:11', '2016-09-08 14:01:11', '', 302, 'http://localhost/wptestsite/302-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
